7736748,-0.06191110,0.04853066,0.05136349,-0.00469793,0.03186671,-0.00266243,0.04902840,0.00976546,-0.01260213,-0.01754398,-0.02074861,-0.01864411,-0.01312764,0.02343421,0.03475905,0.03875375,0.00293611,-0.06209772,0.03424488,0.02746087,-0.03147630,0.07800636,-0.02773445,-0.02881052,-0.07779236,-0.02705492,-0.00556959,-0.03796402,0.00511957,-0.00514650,-0.06326933,0.03842254,0.03014665,0.01336543,0.02999602,-0.07346514,-0.02078260,0.07426884,0.00689061,0.02359307,-0.01272797,-0.04834281]',E'Multitasking\n\nRust''s `Future`s are a form of *cooperative multitasking*. In general, `Future`s\nand `async fn`s should only `.await` on operations and never block.  Some common\nexamples of blocking include locking non-`async` mutexes, joining threads, or\nusing non-`async` library functions (including those in `std`) that perform I/O.\n\nIf a `Future` or `async fn` blocks the thread, inefficient resource usage,\nstalls, or sometimes even deadlocks can occur.\n\nSometimes there is no good `async` alternative for a library or operation. If\nnecessary, you can convert a synchronous operation to an async one with\n[`tokio::task::spawn_blocking`]:\n\n```rust','{"source": "rocket", "version": "0.6", "language": "rust", "title": "Overview", "section_title": "3-overview", "url": "https://github.com/rwf2/Rocket/blob/v0.5-rc/site/guide/3-overview.md", "topics": "rocket,http,3,overview", "categories": "web,rust,rest"}');
